Paul:

If you look at the manual, p2, there are differences between the three 
letters you ask about.  Look at the beginning and ending points and 
whether a vertical line drawn through the beginning would touch the end 
of the letter or not.  The top of Shush is just about directly over the 
bottom of the letter, and it slopes more to the right (i.e. there is 
more of an arch) than Th-ey does.  Thither begins to the left of where 
it ends, probably to insure that it is not mistaken for P-ea..  Th-ey 
ends directly under where it starts.  So, the short answer is, no.  They 
aren&#39;t mirror images of each other.

Bob and Pipe are mirror images except that Bob bends back as it 
approaches the base line in order to make it possible to connect to the 
next letter if it starts at the base line.  This is a change from 
Shavian in which the two letters were mirror images, if my memory is 
correct.

Paige

